{{ref improve|date=November 2014}}

'''Short shackling''' is a technique that [[United States|American]] [[interrogator]]s have been reported to use in the [[War on Terror]]. According to a military report the suspect's hands are [[shackle]]d to an [[eyebolt]] on the floor, so that the suspect is forced to lie in a [[fetal position]] or [[squatting position]].<ref name="CSHRA">{{cite web|url=http://humanrights.ucdavis.edu/projects/the-guantanamo-testimonials-project/testimonies/testimony-of-the-department-of-justice/observations-regarding-specific-techniques/b-prolonged-shackling-and-stress-positions|title=Prolonged Shackling and Stress Positions|publisher=[[The Center for the Study of Human Rights in the Americas]]|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref> It is believed that the suspect's feet are also bound to the eyebolt, similar to [[Hogtie|hogtying]], but this has not been confirmed in any government reports. This [[interrogation]] technique can cause flesh wounds.

